ent of scholarly, journalistic, and pop culture sources.Drawing on his personal experiences and obsessions as well as the thoughts and opinions of mathematicians from Archimedes and Omar Khayyám to such contemporary giants as Alexander Grothendieck and Robert Langlands, Michael Harris reveals the charisma and romance of mathematics as well as its darker side. In this portrait of mathematics as a community united around a set of common intellectual, ethical, and existential challenges, he touches on a wide variety of questions, such as: Are mathematicians to blame for the 2008 financial crisis? How can we talk about the ideas we were born too soon to understand? And how should you react if you are asked to explain number theory at a dinner party?Disarmingly candid, relentlessly intelligent, and richly entertaining, Mathematics without Apologies takes readers on an unapologetic guided tour of the mathematical life, from the philosophy and sociology of mathematics to its reflections in film and popular music, with detours through the mathematical and mystical traditions of Russia, India, medieval Islam, the Bronx, and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMathematiciansxAttitudes. 0aMathematicsxResearch. 7aMATHEMATICS / General.2bisacsh  aA Mathematician's Apology.  aAgainst the Day.  aAlexander Grothendieck.  aArchimedes.  aBirch-Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture.  aDavid Hilbert.  aDrinfel'd upper half-spaces.  aEdward Frenkel.  aG. H. Hardy.  aHerbert Mehrtens.  aJoseph Liouville.  aOmar Khayyám.  aPaul Mogré.  aRites of Love and Math.  aRobert Langlands.  aThomas Pynchon.  acharisma.  acohomology.  acongruences.  adinner party.  aelliptic curves.  aexcellence.  afilms.  afinance mathematics.  amathematical concepts.  amathematical equations.  amathematical finance